"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056041","Department for Transport","false","2019-02-14","<p>Rail is generally an environmentally friendly way to travel or move goods. While recognising the difficulty of making comparisons between different modes of transport, the rail industry estimates that emissions are less than 115 grams of CO2 per passenger kilometre for rail compared to over 130 grams for private cars and over 150 grams for air travel. Each tonne of freight transported by rail reduces carbon emissions by 76 per cent compared to road haulage.</p><p> </p><p>We are nevertheless committed to ensuring that the environmental performance of rail continues to improve. As part of a programme of ongoing work across government and industry to evaluate the railway's impact on carbon emissions, air quality, environmental noise and biodiversity, reports have recently been published on decarbonisation and lineside vegetation.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2019-02-14T14:51:43.167Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056041/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056041/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056041/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-02-06","Railways: Environment Protection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what recent assessment he has made of potential improvements to the environmental performance of railways.","false","Biography information for Bill Wiggin","North Herefordshire","Bill Wiggin","217500"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056042","Ministry of Justice","false","2019-02-14","<p>Our prisons face a range of security challenges including the availability of drugs in prison, and psychoactive substances in particular. As a priority we must toughen security and searching to make it much more difficult for anyone to get contraband such as drugs or mobile phones into prisons. Through the Ten Prison Project we are emphasising the use of technology to search letters, bags and people. Alongside making it much harder to get contraband though the prison gate, we are also closing down other routes, such as by using netting to prevent drones and throw-overs. Improved physical security combined with good existing work on intelligence will help inform priority areas for future investment and development right across the prison estate. In the meantime, across our prisons, we have previously invested £2 million in modern technology such as handheld and portable detection devices. This was followed by another £7 million last year to enhance security in prisons through scanners, improved searching techniques and phone- blocking technology. More recently we have introduced dedicated regional search teams that can target specific individuals or parts of our estate on an intelligence-led basis and vulnerability assessments that cover gate security. We are also seeking to improve the resilience of our prisons to specific security threats through, for example, our investment in intelligence teams, a new Financial Investigations Unit, a new Serious Organised Crime Unit and the changes we are making to our dedicated counter-corruption unit as part of our new anti-corruption strategy.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2019-02-14T17:07:24.387Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056042/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056042/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056042/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2019-02-06","Prisons: Security","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what steps the Government is taking to improve security in prisons.","false","Biography information for Bill Wiggin","North Herefordshire","Bill Wiggin","217501"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056043","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2019-02-11","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the reply given to the hon. Member for Oxford West and Abingdon, Layla Moran, on 1 February 2019, PQ UIN 213461.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2019-02-11T09:49:08.09Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056043/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056043/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056043/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2019-02-06","Environment Protection: EU Grants and Loans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what plans he has to replace (a) EU LIFE funding and (b) EU BEST funding for programmes after 2020.","false","Biography information for Angela Smith","Penistone and Stocksbridge","Angela Smith","217508"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056044","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-02-14","<p>Abortions provided to women from other European Union countries and non-EU countries are funded privately. The European Health Insurance Card cannot be used for an abortion, unless it is an urgent matter which cannot wait until the person can return home.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price","217465","2019-02-14T12:09:29.163Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056044/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056044/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056044/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-02-06","Abortion: Foreign Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, how many free abortions were performed on the NHS for citizens from (a) other EU countries and (b) non-EU countries under reciprocal healthcare arrangements in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Sir Edward Leigh","Gainsborough","Sir Edward Leigh","217464"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056045","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-02-11","<p>As part of the NHS Long Term Plan, NHS England sets out accelerating the uptake of proven, affordable innovations through a new funding mandate for diagnostics, devices and digital innovation. This will apply to innovations that the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) has assessed as cost-saving. NICE will increase the number of evaluations for these products, and these assessments will form the basis of the ‘ready for spread’ status.</p><p> </p><p>Further work to develop implementation plans on criteria and the individualised support described in the NHS Long Term Plan is currently underway, and will be published later this year.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2019-02-11T14:54:11.507Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056045/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056045/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056045/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-02-06","Medical Treatments: Innovation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, with reference to page 77 of the NHS Long Term Plan, what criteria will determine which medical technology innovations are ready for adoption; and what plans are being put in place for the individualised support described in that document.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","217587"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056046","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-02-14","<p>Abortions provided to women from other European Union countries and non-EU countries are funded privately. The European Health Insurance Card cannot be used for an abortion, unless it is an urgent matter which cannot wait until the person can return home.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price","217464","2019-02-14T12:09:29.21Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056046/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056046/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056046/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-02-06","Abortion: Foreign Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what estimate he has made of the cost to the public purse of providing free abortions on the NHS for citizens from (a) other EU countries and (b) non-EU countries under reciprocal healthcare arrangements in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Sir Edward Leigh","Gainsborough","Sir Edward Leigh","217465"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056047","Department for Education","false","2019-02-11","<p>A basic computer is now a mainstream cost of study for all students, disabled or not.</p><p> </p><p>​We believe it is therefore reasonable for students to fund this £200 from their Maintenance Loan. Students from the lowest-income households who started their courses this year have access to the largest ever amounts of cash-in-hand support for their living costs.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2019-02-11T16:57:23.047Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056047/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056047/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056047/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2019-02-06","Disabled Students' Allowances: Computers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answer of 6 February 2019 to Question 213927, if he will make further financial assistance available to students already in receipt of the maximum amount of maintenance loan who are required to pay £200 in order to receive specialist computer hardware allocated to them under the Disabled Student Allowance.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","217449"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056429","Department for Education","false","2019-02-19","<p>It is the department, not the SpLD Assessment Standards Committee, that decides which diagnostic assessments should be recognised as suitable evidence to determine eligibility for Disabled Students’ Allowances. The department is currently considering which accreditation requirements should be met for diagnostic assessments carried out on young people below the age of 16.</p><p>Information regarding the qualifications or professional memberships of those undertaking dyslexia assessments for young people below the age of 16 is not held centrally, nor is it held by the Student Loans Company.</p>",,"Viscount Younger of Leckie","HL13491","2019-02-19T16:42:17.533Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056429/answer","Biography information for Viscount Younger of Leckie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056429/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056429/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2019-02-06","Disabled Students' Allowances: Dyslexia","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether the SpLD Assessment Standards Committee will recognise assessments carried out by Associate Members of the British Dyslexia Association for children under 16 for the purposes of the Disabled Students' Allowance without the need for a second assessment.","false","Biography information for Lord Addington",,"Lord Addington","HL13490"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056430","Department for Education","false","2019-02-19","<p>It is the department, not the SpLD Assessment Standards Committee, that decides which diagnostic assessments should be recognised as suitable evidence to determine eligibility for Disabled Students’ Allowances. The department is currently considering which accreditation requirements should be met for diagnostic assessments carried out on young people below the age of 16.</p><p>Information regarding the qualifications or professional memberships of those undertaking dyslexia assessments for young people below the age of 16 is not held centrally, nor is it held by the Student Loans Company.</p>",,"Viscount Younger of Leckie","HL13490","2019-02-19T16:42:17.58Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056430/answer","Biography information for Viscount Younger of Leckie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056430/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056430/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2019-02-06","Disabled Students' Allowances: Dyslexia","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government how common it is for those holding a British Dyslexia Association Assessment Practising Certificate to be involved with dyslexia assessments for those under the age of 16.","false","Biography information for Lord Addington",,"Lord Addington","HL13491"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056431","Department for Education","false","2019-02-20","<p>I refer the noble Lord to the answer I gave on 6 February 2019 to <a href="https://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Lords/2019-01-24/HL13093/" target="_blank">HL13093</a> and <a href="https://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Lords/2019-01-24/HL13094/" target="_blank">HL13094</a>.</p><p>The eligibility criteria for free school meals (FSM) remains the same following changes to the rollout schedule for Universal Credit (UC), and we will keep the level of the earnings threshold under review following UC rollout. Households that are receiving legacy benefits will continue to access FSM in the same way they do now, and as households migrate to UC in due course, they will remain eligible for FSM throughout the rollout of UC. Our protections mean that even if a household moves above the earnings threshold or ceases to claim benefits, they will continue to receive FSM for the duration of the UC rollout.</p><p>No child that is eligible for and currently receives FSM will lose their entitlement to FSM as a result of UC during the roll out phase, and even more children will benefit by retaining eligibility through the protections we have put in place.</p><p>The department wants to make sure that as many eligible pupils as possible are claiming FSM and to make it as simple as possible for schools and local authorities to determine eligibility. To support this we provide:</p><p>The eligibility checking service to make the checking process as quick and simple as possible for schools and local authorities;</p><p>A model registration form for paper-based applications; and</p><p>Guidance to Jobcentre Plus advisors and work coaches so they can make UC claimants aware that they might be entitled to FSM.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Lord Agnew of Oulton",,"2019-02-20T15:03:24.373Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056431/answer","Biography information for Lord Agnew of Oulton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056431/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056431/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2019-02-06","Free School Meals","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government, further to the Written Answers by Lord Agnew of Oulton on 6 February (HL13093 and HL13094), what assessment they have made of the impact of their decision to delay the roll-out of Universal Credit on the (1) number of children eligible for free school meals, and (2) ability of families to access such meals.","false","Biography information for Lord Bassam of Brighton",,"Lord Bassam of Brighton","HL13492"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056432","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2019-02-18","<p>The Government has studied the report carefully and it will be considered as part of our own independent review of selective licensing. The Department maintains a strong working relationship with the Chartered Institute of Environmental Health (CIEH) and a CIEH representative sits on the project board that oversees the selective licensing review. A final report on the Government review will be published in Spring 2019.</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2019-02-18T15:48:56.467Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056432/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056432/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056432/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2019-02-06","Private Rented Housing: Licensing","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the joint report from the Chartered Institute of Environmental Health and Chartered Institute of Housing A licence to rent published in January; and whether they will support local authorities expanding selective licensing schemes as a way of tackling poor quality housing.","false","Biography information for Lord Bassam of Brighton",,"Lord Bassam of Brighton","HL13493"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056434","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2019-02-19","<p>The Government has no plans to introduce a system of national registration for private landlords. Government is instead focussed on tackling rogue landlords. In April 2018, using powers under the Housing and Planning Act 2016, we introduced a national database of rogue landlords and property agents. We are committed to making this database publicly accessible as soon as parliamentary time allows.</p><p>Moreover, and unlike in Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland, local housing authorities in England are also able to introduce selective licensing of landlords in targeted areas to tackle specific problems, as long as the statutory requirements are met. We have commissioned an independent review of the effectiveness of selective licencing which is on track to report in the spring 2019.</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2019-02-19T17:15:46.037Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056434/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056434/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056434/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2019-02-06","Private Rented Housing: Registration","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment have they made of the case for introducing a nationwide registration of landlords and their properties in England, as in Wales, Scotland and Northern Ireland.","false","Biography information for Lord Bassam of Brighton",,"Lord Bassam of Brighton","HL13494"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056435","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2019-02-18","<p>The Department is actively engaging with stakeholders on selective licensing. The Chartered Institute of Environmental Health sit on the Project Board for the independent review of selective licensing which is currently underway. The Board also includes representatives from two local authorities, as well as the Greater London Authority and the Local Government Association.</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2019-02-18T15:51:24.817Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056435/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056435/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056435/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2019-02-06","Private Rented Housing: Licensing","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether ministers will meet representatives from the Chartered Institute of Environmental Health and Chartered Institute of Housing and representatives from local government to discuss selective licensing schemes.","false","Biography information for Lord Bassam of Brighton",,"Lord Bassam of Brighton","HL13495"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056436","Home Office","false","2019-02-20","<p>Home Office Ministers have regular meetings as part of the process of policy development and delivery. As was the case with previous administrations, it is not the Government's practice to provide details of all such meetings.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2019-02-20T17:25:39.3Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056436/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056436/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056436/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-02-06","Forensic Science Regulator","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government when the Minister of State for Policing and the Fire Service last met the Forensic Science Regulator; and how regularly he has met her since her appointment.","false","Biography information for Lord Borwick",,"Lord Borwick","HL13496"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056437","Department for Transport","false","2019-02-13","<p>During the period between 13 August 2018 (from whence a small number of Leeds services were removed from the timetable) until 1 February 2019 (Monday to Friday only), LNER operated the full timetable on the Leeds to London (both directions) route on 65 of the 123 days. This means that on the other 58, there was at least 1 cancellation of either a Leeds to London or London to Leeds service.</p><p> </p><p>This represents an improvement in operating the full timetable on that route from 31% (in the previous 21 May to 10 August 2018 period) to 53%.</p><p> </p><p>Additionally, the overall number of cancellations halved after implementing the timetable with planned cancellations meaning a more robust service offer for passengers. Between May and July 2018 so called TOC-on-Self cancellations (ie those cancellations within LNER’s control versus external factors) across all LNER services were averaging 89 per period, whilst cancellations between August 2018 and February 2019 were reduced to an average of 44 per period. The provision of extra resilience by implementing the pre-planned cancellations is ensuring a more robust and predictable service for passengers.</p>",,"Baroness Sugg",,"2019-02-13T17:42:54.43Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056437/answer","Biography information for Baroness Sugg","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056437/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056437/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-02-06","Railways: Leeds","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government, further to the Written Answer by Baroness Sugg on 6 February (HL13059), on how many days since 10 August 2018 have London North Eastern Railway cancelled trains in either direction between Leeds and London in addition to the pre-planned cancellations.","false","Biography information for Lord Bradshaw",,"Lord Bradshaw","HL13497"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056439","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-02-13","<p>​We regularly raise our concerns about intercommunal violence with the Nigerian Government at the highest levels. Our High Commission in Abuja is engaging closely with international partners, the Nigerian Government, state governments and the National Economic Council as measures are developed to address the underlying causes of the conflict, including the recently-announced bi-partisan National Livestock Transformation Plan.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2019-02-13T17:18:17.263Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056439/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056439/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056439/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-02-06","Nigeria: Violence","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what representations they have made to the government of Nigeria following the recent violence and deaths associated with Fulani herder militia.","false","Biography information for Baroness Cox",,"Baroness Cox","HL13498"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056440","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-02-20","<p>We have seen no evidence of government involvement in the intercommunal violence which has affected multiple states across Nigeria. We regularly reinforce to the Nigerian authorities the importance of protecting civilians and upholding human rights standards. Any member of the Nigerian security services found to have been involved in human rights violations must be held accountable.</p><p>The UK does not intend to withdraw development and humanitarian assistance from Nigeria, which faces numerous challenges to its future growth and development. The humanitarian crisis in the north-east is worsening, millions of children lack access to clean water, sanitation or education, and conflict continues to affect the oil-rich Delta region. Despite significant natural resources, around a third of Nigerians (60 million) live below the national poverty line with around another third just above; many of them are highly vulnerable and at risk of being trafficked to the UK. The UK is focused on helping Nigeria overcome these challenges.</p>",,"Baroness Goldie",,"2019-02-20T16:27:27.813Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056440/answer","Biography information for Baroness Goldie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056440/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056440/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-02-06","Nigeria: Christianity","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of reports of the government of Nigeria’s involvement in the persecution of Christians in northern and central-belt states; and whether, as a result of any such assessment, they intend to withdraw aid to Nigeria.","false","Biography information for Baroness Cox",,"Baroness Cox","HL13499"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056441","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-02-18","<p>The information is not collected in the format requested.</p>",,"Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford",,"2019-02-18T14:22:57.557Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056441/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056441/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056441/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-02-06","Health Professions: Training","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what estimate they have made of the number of UK students who have become NHS (1) doctors, (2) GPs and (3) nurses in England in each year between 2008 and 2018.","false","Biography information for Lord Dobbs",,"Lord Dobbs","HL13500"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056443","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2019-02-19","<p>There are no plans to transfer responsibility for the UK Holocaust Foundation to the Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport. The Holocaust Memorial Foundation provides independent advice to the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government who has overall responsibility for the delivery of the Holocaust Memorial and Learning Centre.</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2019-02-19T17:15:23.9Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056443/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056443/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056443/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2019-02-06","United Kingdom Holocaust Memorial Foundation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government when responsibility for the UK Holocaust Memorial Foundation will be transferred to the Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport; and how.","false","Biography information for Viscount Eccles",,"Viscount Eccles","HL13501"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056444","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2019-02-19","<p>From 2015/16 to the end of January 2019 the Government has spent £4.8 million on the Holocaust Memorial and Learning Centre programme.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2019-02-19T17:10:04.697Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056444/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056444/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056444/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2019-02-06","National Holocaust Memorial Centre and Learning Service","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what expenditure of public funds has been made to date on the UK Holocaust Memorial and Learning Centre.","false","Biography information for Viscount Eccles",,"Viscount Eccles","HL13502"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056445","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2019-02-20","<p>In January 2015, in response to the Holocaust Commission’s report ‘Britain’s Promise to Remember, the Prime Minister with cross-party support committed £50 million to kick-start a society-wide fundraising effort to deliver the National Memorial and Learning Centre and its wider educational objectives.</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2019-02-20T15:17:30.377Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056445/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056445/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056445/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2019-02-06","National Holocaust Memorial Centre and Learning Service","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what the total cost of the UK Holocaust Memorial and Learning Centre is expected to be; and how this expenditure will be financed.","false","Biography information for Viscount Eccles",,"Viscount Eccles","HL13503"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056446","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2019-02-19","<p>The Holocaust Memorial and Learning Centre will have security arrangements similar to the many other public buildings in Westminster. By using the latest technology and security methodology available we intend for the security aspects to be integrated into the design so it does not impact on the visitor experience.</p><p>To achieve this we are working with security experts, government agencies and the Metropolitan Police to ensure the necessary security measures are put in place.</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2019-02-19T17:15:02.437Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056446/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056446/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056446/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2019-02-06","National Holocaust Memorial Centre and Learning Service","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the risk that the UK Holocaust Memorial and Learning Centre will attract the attention of Holocaust-deniers and anti-Zionists if it is sited close to Parliament.","false","Biography information for Viscount Eccles",,"Viscount Eccles","HL13504"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056447","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2019-02-19","<p>The UK Holocaust Memorial Foundation has engaged extensively with all interested parties, including organisations and members of the Jewish community.</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2019-02-19T17:15:12.543Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056447/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056447/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056447/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2019-02-06","National Holocaust Memorial Centre and Learning Service","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what consultation has taken place, or is intended, with the UK Jewish community about the UK Holocaust Memorial and Learning Centre.","false","Biography information for Viscount Eccles",,"Viscount Eccles","HL13505"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056449","Northern Ireland Office","false","2019-02-14","<p>The Secretary of State for Northern Ireland has commissioned advice on a victims’ pension from the Commissioner for Victims and Survivors for Northern Ireland. We have received some initial advice and look forward to receiving further advice in the near future, following which we will set out next steps.</p>",,"Lord Duncan of Springbank",,"2019-02-14T12:25:00.193Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056449/answer","Biography information for Lord Duncan of Springbank","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056449/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056449/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2019-02-06","Terrorism: Northern Ireland","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether they have received a report from the Commissioner for Victims and Survivors for Northern Ireland about the provision of pensions for those who were severely physically injured in the Northern Ireland Troubles; and if so, what steps they intend to take in regard to that issue.","false","Biography information for Lord Hain",,"Lord Hain","HL13506"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056450","Northern Ireland Office","false","2019-02-18","<p>Work towards bringing forward a victims’ pension is a devolved matter and one of the many reasons why it is so important to have an Executive restored. The Government is aware of how deeply upsetting and frustrating this delay is for those who suffered so much during the Troubles. This is a very complex issue which requires careful consideration, as the Noble Lord will appreciate from his time as Secretary of State for Northern Ireland. That is why the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland has commissioned advice from the Victims Commissioner in Northern Ireland to ensure progress on this important issue. I am grateful to the Noble Lord for our continuing discussions about this matter.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Duncan of Springbank",,"2019-02-18T15:09:07.907Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056450/answer","Biography information for Lord Duncan of Springbank","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056450/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056450/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2019-02-06","Terrorism: Northern Ireland","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government, further to the remarks by Lord Duncan of Springbank on 27 March 2018 (HL Deb, cols 730–761), when they intend to act on the assurances given in those remarks about the provision of pensions for those who were severely physically injured in the Northern Ireland Troubles.","false","Biography information for Lord Hain",,"Lord Hain","HL13507"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056451","Attorney General","false","2019-02-18","<p>Last year the Charity Commission wrote to the Attorney General requesting his consent to refer five questions to the First-Tier Tribunal concerning the Corporation of the Hall of Arts and Sciences – i.e. the Royal Albert Hall, which is a registered charity. While the Charity Commission has the power to refer questions to the Tribunal, it may only do so with the consent of the Attorney General, as set out in section 325 of the Charities Act 2011.</p><p> </p><p>This is a complex case involving the application of modern day charity law to an organisation established over 150 years ago. Before making an assessment as to whether consent should be given to the Commission’s request, both the Corporation and the Commission were invited to make further representations to the Attorney General’s Office. It is important that these are considered carefully, taking into account all relevant factors. While it is not possible to provide an exact estimate as to when a decision will be made, the matter is being given careful thought with a view to reaching a decision as soon as possible.</p>",,"Lord Keen of Elie",,"2019-02-18T13:57:05.797Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056451/answer","Biography information for Lord Keen of Elie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056451/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056451/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2019-02-06","Royal Albert Hall","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government when they estimate that the Attorney General will give his definitive ruling on the points of law arising from the case of the Royal Albert Hall and the Charity Commission.","false","Biography information for Lord Hodgson of Astley Abbotts",,"Lord Hodgson of Astley Abbotts","HL13508"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056452","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2019-02-18","<p>On 9 February we published the Government Response to the Integrated Communities Green Paper and an accompanying Action Plan. The new Integrated Communities Action Plan will drive forward work across government to create socially and economically stronger, more confident and integrated communities. In the Action Plan we commit to a new Cross-Government National English Language Strategy for Autumn 2019. We will engage widely with the sector to help shape its content.</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2019-02-18T15:52:16.68Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056452/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056452/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056452/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2019-02-06","English Language: Education","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government, further to the Integrated Communities Strategy green paper, published in March 2018, when they expect to announce the results of the consultation on methods of improving English language skills.","false","Biography information for Lord Hodgson of Astley Abbotts",,"Lord Hodgson of Astley Abbotts","HL13509"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056454","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-02-20","<p>The Construction, Design and Management Regulations 2015 apply to all National Health Service construction and design work and as such are implemented across all capital investment, including the responsibilities of specific professionals employed. The business case approval process for capital funding implemented by NHS England and NHS Improvement assures appropriate elements of these regulations which are used to review business cases for capital received from the NHS. Staff with estates and facilities services responsibilities across the NHS receive training that should include awareness of their duties and obligations under these regulations, in line with individuals roles and responsibilities, including potential penalties for non-compliance in line with the Health and Safety Offences, Corporate Manslaughter and Food Safety and Hygiene Offences Sentencing Guidelines 2016. NHS Improvement and the Department have not discussed these regulations with the Health and Safety Executive recently.</p>",,"Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","HL13511 ; HL13512 ; HL13513 ; HL13514 ; HL13515","2019-02-20T14:07:45.457Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056454/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056454/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1056454/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-02-06","NHS: Buildings","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the awareness amongst NHS Estates Managers of their obligations under the Construction, Design and Management Regulations 2015 and the application of those Regulations to facilities maintenance operations.","false","Biography information for Lord Hunt of Kings Heath",,"Lord Hunt of Kings Heath","HL13510"
